 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/uzirrix.showPublicProfile>Zirrix</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Global user</span><br>   <font color=#939393>(4/13/00 12:18:26 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Heads up</span><hr size=1> Zirrix looked at the Wizard and said, “I thank you again, cousin, you have been most helpful”. The Wizard looked back and grinned evilly. The Wizards name was Xrath and had meet Zirrix just outside the Halfling city of Rivervale. He was young as Wizards go, far younger then Zirrix’s brother Tzlar, but had the same glittering ambition deep in his violet eyes. Xrath was traveling to the Western Coast of Antonica for some quest. Zirrix had come upon him when one of the minor wandering undead of Kithilcor Forest had made an appearance and was assaulting Xrath. Zirrix had dispatched it and the young Wizard wished to repay his debt. Even though Teir’dal society was built upon a complex web of interconnecting obligations and fealties, most of the Respected Race did not like to be personally indebted to a stranger. That was why Zirrix had helped the Wizard to begin with, he knew the obligation would benefit him. Looking at the Wizard Zirrix said, “ I have matters to attend to in Rivervale, but I do not wish to be “noticed” until it is a time of my choosing. As payment for your debt, you will enspell me with a cloak of invisibility, such that I may proceed to my purpose”. The Wizard smiled, it was an easy casting and would drain his magical reserve very little. Reminding Zirrix that: 1) The moment he took any offensive action, the spell would cancel and he would become visible, and 2) The enchantment was unpredictable and could dispel at any time, he began his casting. As Zirrix faded from sight, he thanked the young Wizard and entered the crevasse that led to the city of Rivervale.<br>
<br>
As Zirrix emerged into the open sunlight of the courtyard, he shielded his eyes. It was almost latesun here in Rivervale. Zirrix had left the gloomy darkness of the Kithilcor Forest only a few moments ago. Such was the world of Norrath. As his eyes adjusted to the burning brightness he scanned the area. There were two guards speaking and few others about. It must be some holiday or such as the streets seemed deserted. At first, Zirrix considered that the Halflings may have been alerted to their danger. But, watching the guards, he decided that was unlikely. They seemed more bored then anxious. One guard was older and had better armor. He looked to be an officer and was probably a match for Zirrix. Normally that wouldn’t stop Zirrix, he did so enjoy killing someone of equal or higher experience. But, here in the city, he knew the other guards would swarm upon him and he would be overwhelmed. No, he would wait, providing his invisibility did not dissipate. After a few minutes, the older guard moved off and the younger came back to his post near the entrance. Zirrix stood still as the guard walked within a hairs breath of him. <br>
<br>
The guard looked to be a few seasons below Zirrix, but not a green recruit. Zirrix thought back to his own soldiers in the Nektulos Forest and snarled a silent curse. How many times had the cowardly lightcrawlers crept  into the Nektulos Forest and ambushed, en masse, the newly appointed sentries. Looking at the guard, Zirrix thought, “Time for a small measure of our vengeance”. Standing in front of the guard, Zirrix reached out and slapped him across the face. He could tell he reappeared when the look of surprise on the guards face turned into one of fear and hatred. The guard pulled his weapon, accusing Zirrix of ruining the Halfling’s land and struck at the Teir’dal Warrior. But, Zirrix was more skilled and in a short time, the guard lay dead. As Zirrix looked at the corpse, he heard a surprised squeak from behind him. Turning he saw a Halfling mother and her young child. If the Mother’s eyes where filled with fear, then the child’s was filled with terror. Moving in a blur, Zirrix clamped his hands over the Mother’s mouth and pulled her into a solid grip with one arm, and impaled the child on his sword with the other. Forcing the mother to watch, Zirrix lifted his blade and shook it so the wriggling, gurgling child slowly slid down to the hilt. Holding her there for a few minutes, Zirrix whispered that he was sent to kill her and her people. He told here that from here, he would sneak to her house and await the rest of her family, where he would spend all night with them, all the long night. As the child stopped moving, Zirrix flung it’s lifeless body into the entrance tunnel and released the mother. <br>
<br>
Waiting just long enough to enjoy the look of horror and anguish in the mothers eyes, Zirrix swung his blade and decapitated her. As her corpse fell to the ground, Zirrix quickly picked up the dying head and looking into it’s dimming eyes said, “Yes mother, all the long night”. After a few moments, seeing no one else was near, Zirrix allowed himself a small smile. He did not usually torment his victims before he killed them, but he was in a good mood and just found the pleasure impossible to suppress. Zirrix did so enjoy a good jest. Dragging the headless body of the mother and the dead guard into the secluded tunnel, he put them next to the child. Next he removed both the guards head and the child’s and put them over to the side. He then though a moment. There were four, no five intruders that entered the Nektulos Forest a few nights past. Zirrix looked down, three heads now, two more to go. He would then prop all of them up on a nearby rock on the Western wall for all to see. He would also leave a note. When the Halflings emerged from their homes to enjoy the sunset, as was their custom during the summer, they would be greeted with a sunset they would not soon forget. A short time later, after killing a merchant and some wander old Grandfather of a hobbit, he waited until all was quiet, glad the old guard hadn’t returned to check on the younger one. As the Halflings went inside for lastmeal and cleared the area, Zirrix arranged his “Presents” and left the note. <br>
<br>
Going back and standing at the exit to the Kithilcor Forest, Zirrix let out a shout of alarm, in Halfling, and ran into the forest. As he entered the forest, he could hear the first shrieks  of horror coming from the people of Rivervale. Once in the forest, he headed back toward the Western Common lands. He thought of the note he left with the heads, it read in Halfling, “You forgot to take bait for your fishing trip. Use these instead, and have pleasant dreams”. Underneath it, he had drawn the picture of a Halfling’s smiling head, resting on a bed. As Zirrix ran through the Forest he decided to brush up on his Halfling, he had a feeling he may have need to write some more notes…           <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/uzirrix.showPublicProfile>Zirrix</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Global user</span><br>   <font color=#939393>(4/14/00 3:19:45 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Eggcitment</span><hr size=1> Zirrix watched as the two Lizardmen fell, slashed and bloody, at his feet. Holding his head up high in victory, he relished the admiring looks from the other hunting parties. He was in the Courtyard of the Forgotten Temple of Cazic-Thule. Around him were a few other hunting parties composed of lower seasoned adventurers. He had just lured out not one, but two heavily armed Lizardmen from the maze. Standing toe to toe, Zirrix had killed them both in brutal combat. The first had tried to run, to seek the aid of more of it’s scaled kind, but it had not gotten far. Many of the adventurers watching him had to form whole parties just to kill one Lizardman, here he was killing two single-handedly. Granted he had been wounded, but still he stood over the corpses, victorious. Zirrix was just preparing to seek more prey when his amulet began to vibrate. The emblem of the Shadows of the Blade was concealed beneath his Crafted Breastplate. The vibrations told of a summons by his Matron, Morrigu of House W’Rath. Finding a secluded spot, Zirrix sat down and began the meditation that would allow him to communicate with his Matron. After a few moments her presence and voice coalesced in his mind. The image said “General, an issue of some importance to the Teir’dal has arisen.…Return to Neriak immediately”. Zirrix sent a mental confirmation and, after bribing a Shaman for a wolfspeed spell, headed North back to his home.<br>
<br>
Some time later, several members of the Shadows of the Blade sat in their recently acquired secret lair as the Matron addressed them. Zirrix listened to the tale of the Golden Egg and the Zan Fi Monks quest. Several members of the Blade did not wish to help, until it was revealed that Innorukk was involved as well. The Dark Creator was sealed in the Citadel just as were the other Gods. Even the Great Battle God Rallos Zek, his God, was imprisoned in a place beyond the stars. The Matron explained that it would be folly to leave a bunch of fence sitting Human Monks with the responsibility of this task. Obviously they knew their own inadequacies and had wisely sought the assistance of the Respected Race. As usual, it would be the children of Neriak who would have to rise to the task. Zirrix pointed out to his Guildmates that it made sense. Because after all, since Norrath was destine to belong to the Teir’dal alone, it was only logical that they be the ones to save it. By releasing the Gods, the Teir’dal would again show their inherent superiority to the lightcrawler races. This would give further proof of their right to rule all.<br>
